{[showcards W:H2 E:HA,H3,DJ S:S3,HK,H6,D6]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown.

You decide a trump lead is called for and lead the \H2. Your partner wins with the \HA and plays the \DJ. South lets this go to dummy's \DK, (but you know he has \DQ), then plays a trump back to his \HK, pulling the 2 outstanding trumps from West and East.

South's next play is the \S3 from his hand. Do you play your \SA or not?

Play the \SA.

Even if South doesn't have the \SK he can establish a \S winner just by leading twice toward the \S Q J. That winner will take care of whatever black-suit loser he may have.

If East has a \C trick it is important to get it established soon. So go up with the \SA and play a \C through dummy's \C A Q. When South tries the \S suit again <b>EAST</b> can win and cash his \CK for the setting trick.

If you play low on South's \S play East will be forced to win the trick and he cannot profitably attack the \C suit from his side.}
[Play "W"]H2

